  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">`GetResourceDetailAsync(string resourceId)` exists, decorated with `[KernelFunction]` + `[Description]` suitable for LLM tool selection.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Returns `ResourceDetail` with full parameter schema, per-parameter `SourceHints`, `SampleInvocations`, governance metadata (`humanGate`, `PhaseRestrictions`, `EvidenceRequired`) — verified by unit test.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Not-found case returns a ProblemDetails-equivalent error or throws a typed exception (per BFF convention) — verified by unit test.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Caller without read permission to the Tool gets forbidden error (ADR-008) — verified by unit test with mocked caller principal.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Parameter schema round-trips intact through serialization (JSON shape stable) — verified by unit test against golden fixture.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">No new NuGet packages added (NFR-10 preserved). Reads via existing Dataverse client.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">NOT exposed via `PublicContracts/IActionEngineFacade.cs` (ADR-013 boundary) — verified by grep.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Supports spec gate G2 (conversational invocation resolves intent → Tool) — the discovery → inspect → invoke flow requires this meta-tool.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    The choice between reading from Dataverse (canonical, fresh, full schema) vs the AI Search index (already in memory, faster) matters here. Design.md §5 specifies Dataverse-canonical with the index as a search projection. Stick with Dataverse reads — `GetResourceDetail` is called less frequently than `FindResources` (one per candidate-inspect, not one per turn).

    `SourceHints` is the critical UX feature: the LLM uses these to decide which parameters to silently auto-resolve from `surfaceContext` vs which to ask the user about. The shape must be expressive enough but not so verbose it bloats token budgets. Mirror the design.md §7.4.1 example shape exactly.

    Caller's read permission MAY be broader than invoke permission. This task's auth check is "can caller see this Tool" not "can caller invoke" — invoke check happens at `InvokeResource` (task 024) or at `IToolHandlerRegistry` dispatch (task 026).
  </notes>

